What is a wavelet as a function?
\layout Standard

Unfortunately, there is no definitive answer to this question.
 While we won't satisfy everyone, we can try to propose a definition.
 Note that this definition does not apply very well in practice because
 for one thing we don't always transform functions, and for another, we
 don't always work with Hilbert spaces.
\layout Standard

Condition 1.
 A wavelet basis must include Riesz basis for families of Hilbert subspaces
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 in a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset 

, we note these Riesz basis (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{basederiez}

\end_inset 

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\psi _{j,i}\right)_{i}\in W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 and we must be able to write 
\begin_inset Formula $H=...\oplus W_{-1}\oplus W_{0}\oplus W_{1}\oplus ...$
\end_inset 

.
 By the Riesz condition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}\sum _{i}|c_{i}|^{2}\leq \left\Vert \sum _{i}c_{i}\psi _{j,i}\right\Vert ^{2}\leq B_{j}\sum _{i}|c_{i}|^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 We say that the wavelet basis is stable if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{j}$
\end_inset 

 are constant (independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Condition 2.
 A wavelet must have null mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\int \psi _{j,i}(x)dx=0$
\end_inset 

 (see 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{momentsnuls}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Condition 3.
 There must exist 
\begin_inset Formula $b>1$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(b\cdot )\in W_{j-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 We choose normally 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2$
\end_inset 

 (dyadic case).
 In other words, in the dyadic case we ask that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(2x)\in W_{j-1}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The first condition might be weakened by replacing 
