What is a discrete wavelet?
\layout Standard

The definition is the same as for wavelets as functions except for the scaling
 property.
 Let's think about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset 

 for example, then wavelets would be vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi _{j,i}$
\end_inset 

 forming Riesz basis on their spanned subspaces and having the null mass
 property.
 Moreover, for practical reasons, we require that wavelets be local.
\layout Standard

Condition 1.
 A wavelet basis must include Riesz basis for families of subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset 

, we note these Riesz basis (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{basederiez}

\end_inset 

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\psi _{j,i}\right)_{i}\in W_{j}$
\end_inset 

 and we must be able to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}=V_{0}\oplus W_{0}\oplus W_{1}\oplus ...\oplus W_{K}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

 is the number of subspaces.
 By the Riesz condition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}\sum _{i}|c_{i}|^{2}\leq \left\Vert \sum _{i}c_{i}\psi _{j,i}\right\Vert ^{2}\leq B_{j}\sum _{i}|c_{i}|^{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 The remaining subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset 

 cannot be represented using the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi _{j,i}$
\end_inset 

 and is sometimes called a scaling subspace.
\layout Standard

Condition 2.
 All wavelet must have null mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \psi _{j,i},1\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset 

 .
\layout Standard

Condition 3.
 Wavelets must be local.
 Define the size of the support of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset 

 to be the smallest integer 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

 such as there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

 with the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{K+k}=0$
\end_inset 

 or is out of range for all 
\begin_inset Formula $|k|>N$
\end_inset 

.
 There must exist 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

 and an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $b>1$
\end_inset 

 such as the size of the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi _{j,i}$
\end_inset 

 is smaller or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{j}N$
\end_inset 

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{K}N\leq n$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

